Reasoning: The claim that every cell in the human body is replaced every seven years is refuted by evidence showing highly variable cell turnover rates across different tissues and cell types. For instance, intestinal epithelial cells are replaced weekly (prop_77395), red blood cells have a circulatory lifespan of approximately 120 days (prop_125166), and a proportion of human cardiac endothelial cells are predicted to renew annually (prop_238676, prop_238287, prop_238687, chunk_3543, chunk_3603, chunk_3540, chunk_3600). In contrast, some cells, like Betz cells in the primary motor cortex, show degeneration over decades, with more than 75% potentially degenerating by the eighth decade of life, indicating a much longer lifespan than seven years and not necessarily replacement (prop_148876, prop_148758). Additionally, the maintenance of naïve T cells in humans relies on extended lifespan and proliferation, further indicating cell lifespans beyond seven years for certain immune cells (prop_119128, prop_119125). These findings collectively demonstrate that there is no single, uniform replacement cycle for all cells in the human body.

